    context: 'Uruguay is the secular country of Latin America — the Catholic Church was disestablished early, divorce was legal before women could vote, and today it has the most progressive social legislation in the hemisphere (marijuana, abortion, same-sex marriage all legal and state-regulated). The welfare state was built in the early 20th century and partially survived everything that followed. The Tupamaro urban guerrillas of the 1960s robbed banks and distributed the money in poor neighborhoods; their most famous member spent 14 years in prison, much of it in solitary, and became president in 2010. José Mujica lived in a farmhouse during his presidency, drove a 1987 VW Beetle, and donated 90% of his salary. The 1973 military coup lasted until 1985 and left a specific kind of political trauma that Uruguayans are still processing. The 2002 banking crisis wiped out savings and drove the poverty rate to 40%. Football is a national religion; Uruguay has won the World Cup twice and still treats that first win in 1930 — on home soil — as a founding myth.',
