    context: 'Paraguay is the only country in Latin America where an indigenous language — Guaraní — is genuinely co-official and spoken by the majority. You grow up speaking both; you switch between them without thinking. The country is landlocked and was almost destroyed in the Triple Alliance War of 1864-70, in which Brazil, Argentina, and Uruguay fought Paraguay for five years and killed between 60 and 70 percent of the population, leaving a ratio of four women to every man in the aftermath. Alfredo Stroessner ruled from 1954 to 1989 — 35 years, the longest personal dictatorship in Latin American history — and the political culture he created persists in the form of land inequality (1% of landowners own 77% of the land), one-party patronage networks, and a specific habit of not saying certain things in certain company. The Archive of Terror, discovered in a police station in 1992, documented Operation Condor and its reach. The memory of the Triple Alliance War is taught with something between grief and pride: we were nearly annihilated. We are still here.',
